<br>
Every other class in the game scales properly, EVERY SINGLE ONE. Magicians are the only class that does not receive significant upgrades past 50. <br>
<br>
Just roll that around your mind. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uxisrene.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Xisrene</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 46<br> <font color=#333333>(1/30/02 9:20:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://xisrene.freewebspace.com/images/xisrenep.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Has Alan's comments helped?</span><hr size=1> The big problem here is that no one (Verant included, Verant especially) has no clear defined concept of exactly what a magician is. We overlap with many classes and no one is quite sure where we fit in.<br>
<br>
For example, all wizards pretty much seem to agree that their purpose is to throw down the big nukes to make things dead fast.<br>
<br>
There is no such clear guiding philosophy beind the magicians. Therefore, you have every magician forming his or her own opinion on what a mage is. Thus, some mages push for larger nukes because that's how they see their mage. Other mages push for stronger pets because that's how their mage makes sense to them. Others see mages as a form of support class, and push for more group utility. An argument could be made for any of these interpretation of the magician. <br>
<br>
* Pre-50, we often rival wizards in our nuking power.<br>
* We have the strongest pets and are practically helpless      <br>
   Without them<br>
* Our summons probably provide more <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> effects</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> we can<br>
   bestow on others than most of the buffing classes (if you <br>
   factor in summoned weapons, food, etc...)<br>
<br>
So the reason I believe mages seem so divisive, is that most people who start a mage have no real concept of what a mage <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> is</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->. And, frankly, at this point you won't be able to establish an overall concept of the mage without greatly upsetting those people who see their mages differently.<br>
 <p><img src="http://xisrene.freewebspace.com/images/xisrenes.jpg" border="0">
